# Error Handling

## Async Operations
- Wrap async logic in try/catch; never leave catch empty
- Re-throw after logging if caller should handle
- Use `trackError(code, message, componentName)` from `useAnalytics()` for user-facing errors

## User-Facing Errors
- Map Firebase/auth error codes to friendly messages (see auth.js `getErrorMessage`)
- Show toast or inline error state; avoid raw error objects in UI

## Logging
- Use `console.error` for unexpected errors; avoid `console.log` for sensitive data
- Remove or gate debug logs (e.g. env var logging) before production
- Analytics: log errors via `trackError` for monitoring

## Examples
```javascript
// ✅ GOOD
try {
  await updateDoc(doc(db, 'Users', id), data);
} catch (error) {
  console.error('Update failed:', error);
  trackError('UPDATE_USER_ERROR', error.message, 'AdminUserManagement');
  setError('Failed to update user. Please try again.');
}
```
